 To generate an automatically updated table of contents in a LaTeX document, you can use the `\tableofcontents` command along with the `hyperref` package. Here's a step-by-step example:

1. First, include the necessary packages in the preamble of your LaTeX document:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage[utf8]{inputenc}
\usepackage{hyperref}
\usepackage{titlesec}

% Set the section format to have no indentation
\titleformat{\section}
{\normalfont\Large\bfseries}{\thesection}{1em}{}
```

2. Next, create the document structure with sections, subsections, etc.:

```latex
\begin{document}

\title{My LaTeX Document}
\author{Author Name}
\date{}
\maketitle

\tableofcontents % Generates the table of contents automatically

\section{Introduction}
Discuss the introduction to your document here.

\subsection{Background}
Provide some background information.

\section{Methodology}
Explain the methodology used in your research.

\subsection{Data Collection}
Describe the data collection process.

\subsection{Data Analysis}
Discuss the data analysis techniques.

\section{Results}
Present the results of your research.

\section{Conclusion}
Summarize your findings and conclusions.

\end{document}
```

In this example, the `hyperref` package is used to enable hyperlink functionality in the PDF output, while the `titlesec` package is used to customize the appearance of section titles. The `\tableofcontents` command generates the table of contents automatically, listing all the sections and subsections in your document with their respective page numbers. The table of contents will be updated whenever you insert, delete, or reorder sections and subsections.

When you compile this LaTeX document, you will see a clickable table of contents at the beginning of your PDF output, which will navigate you to the corresponding sections and subsections as you click on them.

